Ag.name: Gross sectional area
Ag.description: Gross cross-sectional area of a member
Ag.docs: For a rectangular beam: $$$A_g = b \times D$$$

alpha2.name: Alpha2 Coefficient
alpha2.description: Coefficient of concrete compressive area in the "Equivalent compression block method"
alpha2.docs:
$$$\alpha_2$$$ is a reduction factor for concrete strength.

$$$\alpha_2 f'_c$$$ represents the reduced characteristic compressive strength of concrete in the rectangular stress block method.

Acc.name: Area of concrete under compression in the 'rectangular stress block' method
Acc.docs:
The following diagram shows this area:

In a rectanular beam this area can be found by $$\begin{aligned} A_{cc} &= \gamma (d_n) \\ &= \gamma (k_u \times d) \end{aligned}$$

As.name: Area of reinforcement
As.description: Cross-sectional area of reinforcement steel (see Clauses 3.4.3.2 and 13.2.2);
As.docs: This area is foundby adding up the cross sectional areas of all reinforcing steel. The cross sectional areas can be found in

Ast.name: Area of tensile steel
Ast.description: Cross-sectional area of longitudinal tensile reinforcement; or cross-sectional area of reinforcement in the zone that would be in tension under the design loads if the effects of prestress and axial loads are ignored

b.name: Breadth of beam
b.description: Width of a rectangular cross-section or member

Cc.name: Concrete Compression
Cc.docs: This software uses $$$C_c$$$to denote the concrete compression force in the cross section at ultimate load.

d.name: Depth to tensile steel centroid
d.description: 'Effective Depth' of a cross-section in the plane of bending
d.docs:
$$$d$$$ is the depth to the centroid of the tensile steel layers. Finding d requires that you know which layers are in tension.

When deciding which layers to use to find $$$d$$$, only the primary tensile layers are considered. Indiviual bars less than half the size of the largest tensile bar are to be ignored. (these bars might be there for crack control)

Depth.name: Depth of beam
Depth.description: Overall depth of a cross-section in the plane of bending (see Clause 12.5.6)

dfitments.name: Diameter of Fitment
dfitments.docs: The fitment diameter is governed by crack control and sheer strength requirements.

dn.name: Depth to neutral axis
dn.description: Depth to neutral axis, measured from the extreme compressive surface of a cross section.

do.name: Depth to lowest bar
do.description: Distance from the extreme compressive fibre of the concrete to the centroid of the outermost layer of tensile reinforcement or tendons (not less than 0.8D for prestressed concrete members)

Ec.name: Concrete modulus of elasticity
Ec.description: Mean value of the modulus of elasticity of concrete at 28 days

eclass.name: Exposure Classification
eclass.description: Designation indicative of the most severe environment to which a concrete member is to be subjected during its design life (see Table 4.3).

fc.name: Concrete characteristic strength
fc.description: Characteristic compressive (cylinder) strength of concrete at 28 days

fcm.name: Mean Cylinder Strength
fcm.description: Mean value of cylinder strength (see Clause 3.1.1.2)

fcmi.name: Mean In-situ Strength
fcmi.description: Mean value of the in-situ compressive strength of concrete at the relevant age (see Clause 3.1.1.2 and Table 3.1.2)

fctf.name: Concrete characteristic tensile strength
fctf.description: Measured flexural tensile strength of concrete (see Clause 3.1.1.3)

fsy.name: Steel characteristic yield strength
fsy.description: Characteristic yield strength of reinforcement (referred to as Re in AS/NZS 4671), determined in accordance with Clause 3.2.1

gamma.name: Gamma Ratio
gamma.description: Ratio, under design bending or design combined bending and compression, of the depth of the assumed rectangular compressive stress block to k_u * d

I.name: Second moment of area
I.description: Second moment of area of the uncracked concrete cross-section about the centroidal axis

Icr.name: Transformed area second moment of area
Icr.description: Second moment of area of a cracked section with the reinforcement transformed to an equivalent area of concrete

Ief.name: Effective second moment of area
Ief.description: Effective second moment of area (see Clause 8.5.3)

Iefmax.name: Maximum effective second moment of area
Iefmax.description: Maximum effective second moment of area (see Clause 8.5.3)

ku.name: ku Ratio
ku.description: Neutral axis parameter being the ratio, at ultimate strength under any combination of bending and compression, of the depth to the neutral axis from the extreme compressive fibre to d

kuo.name: kuo Ratio
kuo.description: Ratio, at ultimate strength, without axial force of the depth to the neutral axis from the extreme compressive fibre to d_o

Lef.name: Effective Length
Lef.description: Effective span of a member, taken as the lesser of (Ln + D) and L for a beam or slab; or L_n + D/2 for a cantilever

Ln.name: Clear Span
Ln.description: Length of clear span in the direction in which moments are being determined, measured face-to-face of supporting beams, columns or walls, or for a cantilever, the clear projection

Mo.name: Total Static Moment
Mo.description: Total static moment in a span (see Clause 6.10.4.2); or decompression moment (see Clause 8.2.7.2)

Mstar.name: Moment Design Capacity
Mstar.description: Design bending moment at a cross-section

Mu.name: Moment Ultimate Strength - When combined with axial load
Mu.description: Ultimate strength in bending at a cross-section of an eccentrically loaded compressive member

Mub.name: Moment Ultimate Strength - When balanced failure occurs
Mub.description: Particular ultimate strength in bending when k_uo = 0.003/(0.003 + f_sy / E_s) (ie. Balanced failure)

Muo.name: Moment capacity
Muo.description: Ultimate strength in bending, without axial force, at a cross-section

Muomin.name: Minimum design capacity
Muomin.description: Minimum required strength in bending at a critical cross-section (see Clause 8.1.6.1)

phi.name: Capacity reduction factor
phi.description: Capacity reduction factor for design using linear elastic analysis (see Clause 2.2.2)

coderef.data: [There are] .. three ductility classes. These are distinguished in requirements by the letters ‘L’ (low), ‘N’ (normal) and ‘E’ (earthquake), placed immediately after the strength-grade number, corresponding with different minimum values for uniform elongation and maximum stress to yield stress ratio.
500E steels are unlikely to be used in Australia, it being considered that Australia's generally low seismicity can be adequately accounted for by using Normal (N) class steels.
Shape is designated by the letters, R, D, or I, representing plain (Round), Deformed ribbed, or deformed Indented, surfaces respectively.
The standard grades of reinforcing steels are 250N, 300E, 500L, 500N, 500E.

rhoc.name: Concrete Density
rhoc.description: Density of concrete, in kilograms per cubic metre (kg/m3), determined in accordance with Clause 3.1.3

Ts.name: Force in tensile steel
Ts.description: Force developed in the portion of tendons which are under tension. Does not include tendons less than half the diameter of the largest tendon.

Z.name: Section modulus
Z.description: Elastic section modulus of the uncracked cross-section, referred to the extreme fibre at which flexural cracking occurs (see Clause 8.1.6.1)

cover.name: Cover
cover.description: Minimum distance between the outer concrete surfaces and the reinforcing bars.

Es.name: Reo modulus of elasticity (200,000 MPa)
Es.description: Young's modulus of elasticity of reinforcement steel, determined in accordance with Clause 3.2.2
